<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-631-232  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 631 232.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 17 1990 n1214 p34(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Stand up and be counted. (an analysis of the technology supportingthe 1990 US Census) (includes a related article on the firstattempt to automate the census and Herman Hollerith's electrictabulating machine)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mitchell, Amanda.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The 1990 US census has been automated to the point that aspokesman for the Census Bureau says there are no operations leftthat could be automated.andP;  The first commercial computers were usedin the census in 1950, although tabulating machines were used asearly as the census of 1890.andP;  Manual processing of incoming formsat central headquarters had been the rule until the currentcensus, when the estimated population of a quarter of a billionpeople made the task overwhelming.andP;  The job has been dispersed tosome 500 district and processing offices nationwide.andP;  Theinformation is then transmitted to headquarters for analysis.andP;  Ageographical information system (GIS) known as TopologicallyIntegrated Geographic Encoding and Referencing System (TIGER)provides maps for census enumerators as well as the geographiccodes for tabulating information.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationCensusAnalysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>